# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: achuete
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:achuete/achuete] The plant is best known as the source of annatto, a natural orange-red condiment (also called *achiote* or *bijol*) obtained from the waxy arils that cover its seeds.
[src:achuete/achuete] The ground seeds are widely used in traditional dishes in Central and South America, Mexico, and the Caribbean, such as *cochinita pibil*, chicken in *achiote*, *caldo de olla*, and *nacatamal*.
[src:achuete/achuete] Annatto and its extracts are also used as an industrial food coloring to add yellow or orange color to many products such as butter, cheese, margarine, ice creams, meats, and condiments.
[src:achuete/achuete] Some of the indigenous peoples of North, Central, and South America originally used the seeds to make red body paint and lipstick, as well as a spice.
[src:achuete/achuete] For this reason, the *Bixa orellana* is sometimes called the **lipstick tree**.
[src:achuete/achuete] The name *Bixa orellana* was given by Linnaeus.
[src:achuete/achuete] The botanical genus name derives from the aboriginal Taíno word "bixa", while the specific epithet was derived in honor of the Amazon explorer Francisco de Orellana, an early explorer of the Amazon River.
[src:achuete/achuete] The name *achiote* derives from the Nahuatl word for the shrub, *āchiotl* [aːˈt͡ʃiot͡ɬ].
[src:achuete/achuete] It may also be referred to as *aploppas*, or by its original Tupi name *uruku*, *urucu* or *urucum* ("red color"), which is also used for the body paint prepared from its seeds.
[src:achuete/achuete] Colloquial names include *bija*, *roucou*, *orellana*, *annatto*, *achiote*, and many other names used regionally.
[src:achuete/achuete] The nickname, "lipstick tree", derived from use of the dye as a cosmetic.
[src:achuete/achuete] The plant is most well known as the source of the red-orange annatto pigment.
[src:achuete/achuete] The pigment is derived from the waxy aril layer that covers the seeds of the *Bixa orellana* fruit.
[src:achuete/achuete] The red-orange annatto dye is rich in the carotenoid pigments, 80% which consists of bixin (the red pigment) and norbixin or orelline (the yellow pigment).
[src:achuete/achuete] Annatto oil contains tocotrienols, beta-carotene, essential oils, saturated and unsaturated fatty acids, flavonoids, and vitamin C.
[src:achuete/achuete] A chromosome-scale genome assembly of *Bixa orellana* was published in 2026.
[src:achuete/achuete] The assembled genome size is approximately 270 Mb and includes 10 chromosome-scale superscaffolds representing 96.4% of the assembly.
[src:achuete/achuete] The assembly showed a BUSCO completeness of 98.6%, and approximately 56,000 transcripts were annotated.
[src:achuete/achuete] The genome was generated to facilitate studies of genes involved in bixin biosynthesis and regulation.
[src:achuete/achuete] Additionally, *Bixa orellana* is found in substantial wild and cultivated acreages from Mexico to Ecuador, Brazil, and Bolivia.
[src:achuete/achuete] Although an invasive species, it is cultivated in many world regions.
[src:achuete/achuete] During the 16th and 17th centuries, the annatto dye was distributed to Southeast Asia, Africa, the Caribbean, Hawaii and southeastern North America in tropical and subtropical regions through trading exchanges.
[src:achuete/achuete] It became cultivated in tropical regions of Asia, such as India, Sri Lanka, and Java mainly for the dye which the seeds yield.
[src:achuete/achuete] The main commercial producers of *B. orellana* are countries in Latin America (specifically Peru, Brazil and Mexico), which constitute 60% of total world production followed by Africa (27% of total world production) and Asia (12% of total world production).
[src:achuete/achuete] Production statistics are not usually available and would not provide a reliable guide to international trade, since many of the producing countries use significant quantities domestically (e.g., Brazil is a large producer and consumer, needing additional imports).
[src:achuete/achuete] Annual world production of dried annatto seed at the beginning of the 21st century was estimated at 10,000 tons, of which 7,000 tons enter international trade.
[src:achuete/achuete] Peru is the largest exporter of annatto seed, annually about 4,000 tons; Brazil the largest producer, with about 5,000 tons.
[src:achuete/achuete] Kenya exports annually about 1,500 tons annatto seed and extracts and is the second-largest exporter, after Peru.
[src:achuete/achuete] Côte d'Ivoire, Angola, and the Philippines are also exporters.
[src:achuete/achuete] Before synthetic dyes revolutionized industry, *Bixa orellana* (which is the only plant to produce the pigment bixin) was planted commercially.
[src:achuete/achuete] The pigment is extracted from the pericarp of the seeds through use of alkaline water, vegetable oil, or organic solvents.
[src:achuete/achuete] The annatto pigment has global economic significance, as it is one of the most widely used natural dyes to color food, cosmetics and pharmaceutical products.
[src:achuete/achuete] It is used commonly in foods because the coloring does not alter the flavor and is not toxic, though it may trigger allergic reactions in those who are sensitive.
[src:achuete/achuete] It is mainly used to dye ice cream, meats, dairy products (cheeses, butter and margarine) and condiments.
[src:achuete/achuete] Cosmetic products include lipstick, hair coloring products, nail polish, soaps, lacquers and paints.
[src:achuete/achuete] Ground *Bixa orellana* seeds are often mixed with other seeds or spices to form a paste or powder for culinary uses in Latin American, Jamaican, Chamorro, and Filipino cuisines.
[src:achuete/achuete] The seeds are heated in oil or lard to extract their dye and flavor for use in dishes and processed foods such as cheese, butter, soup, gravy, sauces, cured meats, and other items.
[src:achuete/achuete] The seeds impart a subtle flavor and aroma and a yellow to reddish-orange color to food.
[src:achuete/achuete] A condiment called *sazón* is commonly used in Spanish, Latin American, and Caribbean cuisine for meats and fish.
[src:achuete/achuete] The Spanish word *sazón* means "season" or "seasoning".
[src:achuete/achuete] *Sazón* is made with ground *Bixa orellana* seeds and packaged into small, disposable foil packets for easy use.
[src:achuete/achuete] Additionally, cumin, coriander seeds, salt, and garlic powder are included in these *sazón* condiment packets.
[src:achuete/achuete] On Spanish-speaking Caribbean islands, the annatto pigment is also used to make yellow rice and is sometimes added to sofrito.
[src:achuete/achuete] Additionally, in the French Caribbean, it is added to a fish or pork stew called blaff.
[src:achuete/achuete] In Brazil, a powder known as *colorau* or *colorífico* is made from the ground seeds combined with filler seeds like maize.
[src:achuete/achuete] This powder is similar to and sometimes replaces paprika.
[src:achuete/achuete] In Nicaragua, the most common way achiote is used in their cuisine and dishes is in the form of a paste.
[src:achuete/achuete] It is used in many national dishes, such as chancho con yuca, nacatamal, and fritanga.
[src:achuete/achuete] The Yucatecan condiment called *recado rojo*, or "achiote paste", is made from ground *Bixa orellana* seeds combined with other spices and is a mainstay in Mexican and Belizean cuisines.
[src:achuete/achuete] One major traditional use of the *Bixa orellana* plant was for body, face, and hair paint among various tribes and ancient civilizations either for decorative purposes or as omens to ward off evil spirits and illnesses.
[src:achuete/achuete] It has been reported to be used by Brazilian native tribes, the native Taínos in Puerto Rico, the Tsáchila of Ecuador and different Amazonian tribes.
[src:achuete/achuete] As a result of the Spanish Conquest, the *Bixa orellana* was introduced to peoples like the Aztecs, Incas and Mochicas, who showed evidence of later use.
[src:achuete/achuete] The Aztecs also apparently used the annatto pigment as red ink for manuscript painting in the 16th century.
[src:achuete/achuete] The plant is valued for its stem fiber to make rope mats and for the adhesive gum.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] As the study of biology became increasingly specialized, specific codes were adopted for different types of organism.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] To an end-user who only deals with names of species, with some awareness that species are assignable to genera, families, and other taxa of higher ranks, it may not be noticeable that there is more than one code, but beyond this basic level these are rather different in the way they work.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (which may be shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name,** or a **scientific name**; more informally it is also historically called a **Latin name**.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In the zoological code, ICZN, the system is also called **binominal nomenclature** (using the suffix *-inal* instead of *-ial*), meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the **specific name** or **specific epithet** – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] *Tyrannosaurus rex* is likely the most widely known non-human binomial.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The *formal* introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated exposition of plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The introduction of two-part names (binominal nomenclature) for species by Linnaeus was a welcome simplification because as our knowledge of biodiversity expanded, so did the length of the names, many of which had become unwieldy.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] With all naturalists worldwide adopting binominal nomenclature, there arose several schools of thought about the details.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] It became ever more apparent that a detailed body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] From the mid-19th century onwards, there were several initiatives to arrive at worldwide-accepted sets of rules.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The starting point, that is the time from which these codes are in effect (usually retroactively), varies from group to group, and sometimes from rank to rank.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In botany and mycology, the starting point is often 1 May 1753 (Linnaeus, *Species plantarum*).
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In zoology, it is 1 January 1758 (Linnaeus, *Systema Naturae*, 10th Edition).
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] On the other hand, bacteriology started anew, making a clean sweep in 1980 (Skerman et al., "Approved Lists of Bacterial Names"), although maintaining the original authors and dates of publication.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] There are also differences in the way codes work.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] For example, the *ICN* (the code for algae, fungi and plants) forbids tautonyms, while the *ICZN* (the animal code) allows them.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] These codes differ in terminology, and there is a long-term project to "harmonize" this.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] For instance, the *ICN* uses "valid" in "valid publication of a name" (=the act of publishing a formal name), with "establishing a name" as the *ICZN* equivalent.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The *ICZN* uses "valid" in "valid name" (="correct name"), with "correct name" as the *ICN* equivalent.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Harmonization is making very limited progress.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] There are differences in respect of what kinds of types are used.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The bacteriological code prefers living type cultures, but allows other kinds.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] There has been ongoing debate regarding which kind of type is more useful in a case like cyanobacteria.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] A more radical approach was made in 1997 when the IUBS/IUMS International Committee on Bionomenclature (ICB) presented the long debated *Draft BioCode*, proposed to replace all existing *Codes* with a harmonization of them.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The originally planned implementation date for the BioCode draft was January 1, 2000, but agreement to replace the existing *Codes* was not reached.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In 2011, a revised *BioCode* was proposed that, instead of replacing the existing *Codes*, would provide a unified context for them, referring to them when necessary.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Changes in the existing codes are slowly being made in the proposed directions.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] However, participants of the last serious discussion of the draft BioCode concluded that it would probably not be implemented in their lifetimes.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Many authors encountered problems in using the Linnean system in phylogenetic classification.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In fact, early proponents of rank-based nomenclature, such as Alphonse de Candolle and the authors of the 1886 version of the American Ornithologists' Union code of nomenclature already envisioned that in the future, rank-based nomenclature would have to be abandoned.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Another *Code* that was developed since 1998 is the *PhyloCode*, which now regulates names defined under phylogenetic nomenclature instead of the traditional Linnaean nomenclature.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] This new approach requires using phylogenetic definitions that refer to "specifiers", analogous to "type" under rank-based nomenclature.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Such definitions delimit taxa under a given phylogeny, and this kind of nomenclature does not require use of absolute ranks.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The *Code* took effect in 2020, with the publication of Phylonyms, a monograph that includes a list of the first names established under that code.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Some protists, sometimes called **ambiregnal protists**, have been considered to be both protozoa and algae, or protozoa and fungi, and names for these have been published under either or both of the *ICZN* and the *ICN*.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The resulting double language throughout protist classification schemes resulted in confusion.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Slime molds, plasmodial forms and other "fungus-like" organisms claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include mycetozoans, plasmodiophorids, acrasids, and labyrinthulomycetes.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Fungi claimed by both protozoologists and mycologists include chytrids, blastoclads, and the gut fungi.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Other problematic groups are the Cyanobacteria (ICNP/ICN), the Rozellida and Microsporidia (ICZN/ICN).
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The zoological code does not regulate names of taxa lower than subspecies or higher than superfamily.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] There are many attempts to introduce some order on the nomenclature of these taxa, including the PhyloCode, the Duplostensional Nomenclatural System, and circumscriptional nomenclature.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] The botanical code is applied primarily to the ranks of superfamily and below.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] There are some rules for names above the rank of superfamily, but the principle of priority does not apply to them, and the principle of typification is optional.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] These names may be either automatically typified names or be descriptive names.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] In some circumstances, a taxon has two possible names (e.g., Chrysophyceae Pascher, 1914, *nom. descrip.*; Hibberd, 1976, *nom. typificatum*).
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Descriptive names are problematic, once that, if a taxon is split, it is not obvious which new group takes the existing name.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] Meanwhile, with typified names, the existing name is taken by the new group that still bears the type of this name.
[src:achuete/biological-nomenclature] However, typified names present special problems for microorganisms.
[src:achuete/common-name] In biology, a **common name** is a name of a taxon or organism that is based on the normal language of everyday life.
[src:achuete/common-name] It is often contrasted with the scientific name for the same organism, which is often based in Latin.
[src:achuete/common-name] Common names can be used frequently, but that is not always the case.
[src:achuete/common-name] Creating an "official" list of common names can also be an attempt to standardize the use of common names, which can sometimes vary a great deal between one part of a country and another, as well as between one country and another country, even where the same language is spoken in both places.
[src:achuete/common-name] A common name intrinsically plays a part in a classification of objects, typically an incomplete and informal classification, in which some names are degenerate examples in that they are unique and lack reference to any other name, as is the case with say, *ginkgo*, *okapi*, and *ratel*.
[src:achuete/common-name] The form of scientific names for organisms, called binomial nomenclature, is superficially similar to the noun-adjective form of vernacular names or common names which were used by non-modern cultures.
[src:achuete/common-name] A collective name such as *owl* was made more precise by the addition of an adjective such as *screech*.
[src:achuete/common-name] Linnaeus himself published a flora of his homeland Sweden, *Flora Svecica* (1745), and in this, he recorded the Swedish common names, region by region, as well as the scientific names.
[src:achuete/common-name] The Swedish common names were all binomials (e.g. plant no.
[src:achuete/common-name] 85 Ren-losta); the vernacular binomial system thus preceded his scientific binomial system.
[src:achuete/common-name] The geographic range over which a particularly common name is used varies; some common names have a very local application, while others are virtually universal within a particular language.
[src:achuete/common-name] Some such names even apply across ranges of languages; the word for *cat*, for instance, is easily recognizable in most Germanic and many Romance languages.
[src:achuete/common-name] Many vernacular names, however, are restricted to a single country and colloquial names to local districts.
[src:achuete/common-name] Some languages also have more than one common name for the same animal.
[src:achuete/common-name] For example, in Irish, there are many terms that are considered outdated but still well-known for their somewhat humorous and poetic descriptions of animals.
[src:achuete/common-name] Common names are used in the writings of both professionals and laymen.
[src:achuete/common-name] Many examples of such common names simply are attempts to translate the scientific name into English or some other vernacular.
[src:achuete/common-name] Such translation may be confusing in itself, or confusingly inaccurate, for example, *gratiosus* does not mean "gracile" and *gracilis* does not mean "graceful".
[src:achuete/common-name] Various bodies and the authors of many technical and semi-technical books do not simply adapt existing common names for various organisms; they try to coin (and put into common use) comprehensive, useful, authoritative, and standardised lists of new names.
[src:achuete/common-name] Other attempts to reconcile differences between widely separated regions, traditions, and languages, by arbitrarily imposing nomenclature, often reflect narrow perspectives and have unfortunate outcomes.
[src:achuete/common-name] For example, members of the genus *Burhinus* occur in Australia, Southern Africa, Eurasia, and South America.
[src:achuete/common-name] A recent trend in field manuals and bird lists is to use the name "thick-knee" for members of the genus.
[src:achuete/common-name] This, in spite of the fact that the majority of the species occur in non-English-speaking regions and have various common names, not always English.
[src:achuete/common-name] For example, "Dikkop" is the centuries-old South African vernacular name for their two local species: *Burhinus capensis* is the Cape dikkop (or "gewone dikkop", not to mention the presumably much older Zulu name "umBangaqhwa"); *Burhinus vermiculatus* is the "water dikkop".
[src:achuete/common-name] The thick joints in question are not even, in fact, the birds' knees, but the intertarsal joints—in lay terms the ankles.
[src:achuete/common-name] Furthermore, not all species in the genus have "thick knees", so the thickness of the "knees" of some species is not of clearly descriptive significance.
[src:achuete/common-name] The family Burhinidae has members that have various common names even in English, including "stone curlews", so the choice of the name "thick-knees" is not easy to defend but is a clear illustration of the hazards of the facile coinage of terminology.
[src:achuete/common-name] For collective nouns for various subjects, see a list of collective nouns (e.g. a flock of sheep, pack of wolves).
[src:achuete/common-name] Some organizations have created official lists of common names, or guidelines for creating common names, hoping to standardize the use of common names.
[src:achuete/common-name] The AFNS has been an official Australian Standard since July 2007 and has existed in draft form (The Australian Fish Names List) since 2001.
[src:achuete/common-name] Seafood Services Australia (SSA) serve as the Secretariat for the AFNC.
[src:achuete/common-name] The Entomological Society of America maintains a database of official common names of insects, and proposals for new entries must be submitted and reviewed by a formal committee before being added to the listing.
[src:achuete/common-name] Efforts to standardize English names for the amphibians and reptiles of North America (north of Mexico) began in the mid-1950s.
[src:achuete/common-name] The dynamic nature of taxonomy necessitates periodical updates and changes in the nomenclature of both scientific and common names.
[src:achuete/common-name] The Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles (SSAR) published an updated list in 1978, largely following the previous established examples, and subsequently published eight revised editions ending in 2017.
[src:achuete/common-name] More recently the SSAR switched to an online version with a searchable database.
[src:achuete/common-name] Standardized names for the amphibians and reptiles of Mexico in Spanish and English were first published in 1994, with a revised and updated list published in 2008.
[src:achuete/common-name] A set of guidelines for the creation of English names for birds was published in *The Auk* in 1978.
[src:achuete/common-name] It gave rise to *Birds of the World: Recommended English Names* and its Spanish and French companions.
[src:achuete/common-name] The Academy of the Hebrew Language publish from time to time short dictionaries of common name in Hebrew for species that occur in Israel or surrounding countries e.g. for Reptilia in 1938, Osteichthyes in 2012, and Odonata in 2015.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Filipino, like other Austronesian languages, commonly uses verb-subject-object order, but can also use subject-verb-object order.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Filipino follows the trigger system of morphosyntactic alignment that is common among Philippine languages.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] It is an agglutinative language but can also display inflection.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] It is not a tonal language and can be considered a pitch-accent language and a syllable-timed language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The Philippines is a multilingual state with 175 living languages originating and spoken by various ethno-linguistic groups.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Many of these languages descend from a common Malayo-Polynesian language due to the Austronesian migration from Taiwan.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The common Malayo-Polynesian language split into different languages, and usually through the Malay language, the lingua franca of maritime Southeast Asia, these were able to adopt terms that ultimately originate from other languages such as Japanese, Hokkien, Sanskrit and Arabic.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The Malay language was generally used by the ruling classes and merchants for international communication.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Spanish intrusion into the Philippine islands started in 1565 with the fall of Cebu.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] After its fall to the Spaniards, Manila was made the capital of the Spanish settlement in Asia due to the city's commercial wealth and influence, its strategic location, and Spanish fears of raids from the Portuguese and the Dutch.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The first dictionary of Tagalog, published as the *Vocabulario de la lengua tagala*, was written by the Franciscan Pedro de San Buenaventura, and published in 1613 by the "Father of Filipino Printing" Tomás Pinpin in Pila, Laguna.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] A latter book of the same name was written by Czech Jesuit missionary Paul Klein (known locally as Pablo Clain) at the beginning of the 18th century.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Klein spoke Tagalog and used it actively in several of his books.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] He wrote a dictionary, which he later passed to Francisco Jansens and José Hernández.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Further compilation of his substantial work was prepared by Juan de Noceda and Pedro de Sanlúcar and published as **Vocabulario de la lengua tagala** in Manila in 1754 and then repeatedly re-edited, with the latest edition being published in 2013 in Manila.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Spanish served in an official capacity as language of the government during the Spanish period.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Spanish played a significant role in unifying the Philippines, a country made up of over 7,000 islands with a multitude of ethnicities, languages, and cultures.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Before Spanish rule, the archipelago was not a unified nation, but rather a collection of independent kingdoms, sultanates, and tribes, each with its own language and customs.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] During the American colonial period, English became an additional official language of the Philippines alongside Spanish; however, the number of speakers of Spanish steadily decreased.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The United States initiated policies that led to the gradual removal of Spanish from official use in the Philippines.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This was not done through an outright ban, but rather through a strategic shift in language policy that promoted English as the primary language for education, governance, and law.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Spanish was designated an optional and voluntary language under the 1987 Constitution, along with Arabic.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] While Spanish and English were considered "official languages" during the American colonial period, there existed no "national language" initially.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] On November 13, 1936, the first National Assembly of the Philippine Commonwealth approved Commonwealth Act No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 184; creating the Institute of National Language (later the Surián ng Wikang Pambansâ or SWP) and tasking it with making a study and survey of each existing native language, hoping to choose which was to be the base for a standardized national language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Quezon later appointed representatives for each major regional language to form the NLI.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] De Veyra, who sat as the chair of the Institute and as the representative of Samar-Leyte-Visayans, the Institute's members were composed of Santiago A.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Fonacier (representing the Ilokano-speaking regions), Filemon Sotto (the Cebu-Visayans), Casimiro Perfecto (the Bikolanos), Felix S.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Sales Rodriguez (the Panay-Visayans), Hadji Butu (the languages of Muslim Filipinos), and Cecilio Lopez (the Tagalogs).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The Institute of National Language adopted a resolution on November 9, 1937, recommending Tagalog to be basis of the national language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] On December 30, 1937, President Quezon issued Executive Order No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 1937, approving the adoption of Tagalog as the language of the Philippines, and proclaimed the national language of the Philippines so based on the Tagalog language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Quezon himself was born and raised in Baler, Aurora, which is a native Tagalog-speaking area.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The order stated that it would take effect two years from its promulgation.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] It is not divided into smaller daughter languages, as Visayan or Bikol are.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Its literary tradition is the richest of all Philippine languages, the most developed and extensive (mirroring that of the Tuscan language *vis-à-vis* Italian).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] From at least before 1935, more books were written in Tagalog than in any other Philippine language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Tagalog has always been the language of Manila, the political centre of the Philippines in much of its history as a multiethnic country and a considerable economic centre of the Philippine islands since time immemorial.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Tagalog also became a choice for some non-Tagalog Filipino revolutionary leaders and nationalists in some of their publications, especially if they were to publish in Manila.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] On June 7, 1940, the Philippine National Assembly passed Commonwealth Act No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 570 declaring that the Filipino national language would be considered an official language effective July 4, 1946 (coinciding with the country's expected date of independence from the United States).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] That same year, the *Balarílà ng Wikang Pambansâ* (English: Grammar of the National Language) of grammarian Lope K.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Santos introduced the 20-letter Abakada alphabet which became the standard of the national language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The alphabet was officially adopted by the Institute for the Tagalog-Based National Language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] During World War II, the Japanese occupiers encouraged the use of the national language rather than English in schools.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The Tagalog-based national language was, therefore, propagated not only in education but also in mass media and in official communication.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The census for 1948 reported that 7,126,913 people or 37.11% of the population spoke the language, representing an increase of 11.7% from the 1939 figure of 4,068,565.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Of these seven million people, 47.7% learnt it as a second language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In 1959, the language became known as *Pilipino* in an effort to disassociate it from the Tagalog ethnic group.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The changing of the name did not, however, result in universal acceptance among non-Tagalogs, especially Cebuanos who had previously not accepted the 1937 selection.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The 1960s saw the rise of the purist movement where new words were being coined to replace loanwords.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This era of "purism" by the SWP sparked criticisms by a number of persons.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Two counter-movements emerged during this period of "purism": one campaigning against Tagalog and the other campaigning for more inclusiveness in the national language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In 1963, Negros Occidental congressman Innocencio V.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Ferrer took a case reaching the Supreme Court questioning the constitutionality of the choice of Tagalog as the basis of the national language (a case ruled in favor of the national language in 1970).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Accusing the national language as simply being Tagalog and lacking any substantial input from other Philippine languages, Congressman Geruncio Lacuesta eventually led a "Modernizing the Language Approach Movement" (MOLAM).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Lacuesta hosted a number of "anti-purist" conferences and promoted a "Manila Lingua Franca" which would be more inclusive of loanwords of both foreign and local languages.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This movement quietened down following the death of Lacuesta.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The national language issue was revived once more during the 1971 Constitutional Convention.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] While there was a sizable number of delegates in favor of retaining the Tagalog-based national language, majority of the delegates who were non-Tagalogs were even in favor of scrapping the idea of a "national language" altogether.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] A compromise was reached and the wording on the 1973 constitution made no mention of dropping the national language Pilipino or made any mention of Tagalog.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Instead, the 1973 Constitution, in both its original form and as amended in 1976, designated English and Pilipino as official languages and provided for development and formal adoption of a common national language, termed *Filipino*, to replace Pilipino.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In 1987, a new constitution designated Filipino as the national language and, along with English, as an official language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] That constitution included several provisions related to the Filipino language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Section 17(d) of Executive Order 117 of January 30, 1987 renamed the *Institute of National Language* as *Institute of Philippine Languages*.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 7104, approved on August 14, 1991, created the *Komisyon sa Wikang Filipino* (Commission on the Filipino Language, or KWF), superseding the Institute of Philippine Languages.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The KWF reports directly to the President and was tasked to undertake, coordinate and promote researches for the development, propagation and preservation of Filipino and other Philippine languages.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] However, as with the 1973 and 1987 Constitutions, 92-1 went neither so far as to categorically identify, nor so far as to dis-identify this language as Tagalog.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Definite, absolute, and unambiguous interpretation of 92–1 is the prerogative of the Supreme Court in the absence of directives from the KWF, otherwise the sole legal arbiter of the Filipino language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Filipino was presented and registered with the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), by Ateneo de Manila University student Martin Gomez, and was added to the ISO registry of languages on September 21, 2004, with it receiving the ISO 639-2 code *fil*.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] On August 22, 2007, it was reported that three Malolos City regional trial courts in Bulacan decided to use Filipino, instead of English, in order to promote the national language.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Twelve stenographers from Branches 6, 80 and 81, as model courts, had undergone training at Marcelo H. del Pilar College of Law of Bulacan State University following a directive from the Supreme Court of the Philippines.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] De la Rama said it was the dream of Chief Justice Reynato Puno to implement the program in other areas such as Laguna, Cavite, Quezon, Aurora, Nueva Ecija, Batangas, Rizal, and Metro Manila, all of which mentioned are natively Tagalog-speaking.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Since 1997, a month-long celebration of the national language occurs during August, known in Filipino as *Buwan ng Wika* (Language Month).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Previously, this lasted only a week and was known as *Linggo ng Wika* (Language Week).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The celebration coincides with the month of birth of President Manuel L.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Quezon, regarded as the "Ama ng Wikang Pambansa" (Father of the national language).
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 35 of March 26 provided for a week-long celebration of the national language. this celebration would last from March 27 until April 2 each year, the last day coinciding with birthday of the Filipino writer Francisco Baltazar, author of the Tagalog epic *Florante at Laura*.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 12 of March 26 provided that the week of celebration would be from March 29 to April 4 every year.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This proclamation was amended the following year by President Ramon Magsaysay by Proclamation No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 186 of September 23, moving the dates of celebration to August 13–19, every year.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Now coinciding with the birthday of President Manuel L.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] The reason for the move being given that the original celebration was a period "outside of the school year, thereby precluding the participation of schools in its celebration".
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In 1988, President Corazon Aquino signed Proclamation No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 19, reaffirming the celebration every August 13 to 19.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In 1997, the celebration was extended from a week to a month by Proclamation 1041 of July 15 signed by President Fidel V.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Jaime Lopez, former representative for Manila's 2nd congressional district, argued that the current state of the Filipino language is contrary to the intention of Republic Act (RA) No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 7104 that requires that the national language be developed and enriched by the lexicon of the country's other languages.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Today's Filipino language is best described as "Tagalog-based".
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This is similar to the comparison between Castilian and Spanish, or Mandarin and Chinese.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Political designations aside, Tagalog and Filipino are linguistically the same, sharing, among other things, the same grammatical structure.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] He said further that this is contrary to the intention of Republic Act No.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] 7104, which requires that the national language be developed and enriched by the lexicon of the country's other languages, something toward which the commission was working.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] In connection with the use of Filipino, or specifically the promotion of the national language, the related term *Tagalista* is frequently used.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] This is a translation of Article 1 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:achuete/filipino-language] Usually, the diacritics are not written, and the syntax and grammar are based on that of Tagalog.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] As of 2023, this edition of the standard has been officially withdrawn and replaced by ISO 639:2023.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-3 extends the ISO 639-2 alpha-3 codes with an aim to cover all known natural languages.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The extended language coverage was based primarily on the language codes used in the *Ethnologue* (volumes 10–14) published by SIL International, which is now the registration authority for ISO 639-3.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] It provides an enumeration of languages as complete as possible, including living and extinct, ancient and constructed, major and minor, written and unwritten.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] However, it does not include reconstructed languages such as Proto-Indo-European.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-3 is intended for use as metadata codes in a wide range of applications.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] It is widely used in computer and information systems, such as the Internet, in which many languages need to be supported.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] In archives and other information storage, it is used in cataloging systems, indicating what language a resource is in or about.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The codes are also frequently used in the linguistic literature and elsewhere to compensate for the fact that language names may be obscure or ambiguous.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-3 includes all languages in ISO 639-1 and all individual languages in ISO 639-2.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-1 and ISO 639-2 focused on major languages, most frequently represented in the total body of the world's literature.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Since ISO 639-2 also includes language collections and Part 3 does not, ISO 639-3 is not a superset of ISO 639-2.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Where B and T codes exist in ISO 639-2, ISO 639-3 uses the T-codes.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] As of 23 January 2023, the standard contains 7,916 entries.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Machine-readable data files are provided by the registration authority.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Mappings from ISO 639-1 or ISO 639-2 to ISO 639-3 can be done using these data files.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-3 is intended to assume distinctions based on criteria that are not entirely objective.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] It is not intended to document or provide identifiers for dialects or other sub-language variations.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Nevertheless, judgments regarding distinctions between languages may be subjective, particularly in the case of language varieties without established literary traditions, usage in education or media, or other factors that contribute to language conventionalization.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Therefore, the standard should not be regarded as an authoritative statement of what distinct languages exist in the world (about which there may be substantial disagreement in some cases), but rather simply one useful way for identifying different language varieties precisely.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Since the code is three-letter alphabetic, one upper bound for the number of languages that can be represented is 26 × 26 × 26 = 17,576.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Since ISO 639-2 defines special codes (4), a reserved range (520) and B-only codes (22), 546 codes cannot be used in part 3.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The upper bound gets even stricter if one subtracts the language collections defined in 639-2 and the ones yet to be defined in ISO 639-5.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Reference names may only use a subset of ASCII characters.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Reference names may also include any of five ASCII punctuation marks (space, hyphen-minus, apostrophe and the parentheses), and within parentheses the full stop and the ten digits.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Alternative names may use proper language orthography, if Latin, or transliteration into Latin script that contains additional characters.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] There are 58 languages in ISO 639-2 which are considered, for the purposes of the standard, to be "macrolanguages" in ISO 639-3.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Some of these macrolanguages had no individual language as defined by ISO 639-3 in the code set of ISO 639-2, e.g.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Others like `nor` (Norwegian) had their two individual parts (`nno` (Nynorsk), `nob` (Bokmål)) already in ISO 639-2.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] `arb`, Standard Arabic) that were considered by ISO 639-2 to be dialects of one language (`ara`) are now in ISO 639-3 in certain contexts considered to be individual languages themselves.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] This is an attempt to deal with varieties that may be linguistically distinct from each other, but are treated by their speakers as two forms of the same language, e.g. in cases of diglossia.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] A complete list is available on the ISO 639-3 registrar's website.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] "A collective language code element is an identifier that represents a group of individual languages that are not deemed to be one language in any usage context." These codes do not precisely represent a particular language or macrolanguage.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] While ISO 639-2 includes three-letter identifiers for collective languages, these codes are excluded from ISO 639-3.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Hence ISO 639-3 is not a superset of ISO 639-2.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] ISO 639-5 defines 3-letter collective codes for language families and groups, including the collective language codes from ISO 639-2.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Four codes are set aside in ISO 639-2 and ISO 639-3 for cases where none of the specific codes are appropriate.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] These are intended primarily for applications like databases where an ISO code is required regardless of whether one exists.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] In addition, 520 codes in the range `qaa`–`qtz` are 'reserved for local use'.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] For example, Rebecca Bettencourt assigns a code to constructed languages, and new assignments are made upon request.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The code table for ISO 639-3 is open to changes.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The code assigned to a language is not changed unless there is also a change in denotation.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Changes are made according to an annual cycle.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Every request is given a minimum period of three months for public review.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The ISO 639-3 Web site has pages that describe "scopes of denotation" (languoid types) and types of languages, which explain what concepts are in scope for encoding and certain criteria that need to be met.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] For example, constructed languages can be encoded, but only if they are designed for human communication and have a body of literature, preventing requests for idiosyncratic inventions.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] The registration authority documents on its Web site instructions made in the text of the ISO 639-3 standard regarding how the code tables are to be maintained.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] It also documents the processes used for receiving and processing change requests.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] A change request form is provided, and there is a second form for collecting information about proposed additions.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] When submitted, requests are initially reviewed by the registration authority for completeness.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] When a fully documented request is received, it is added to a published Change Request Index.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Also, announcements are sent to the general LINGUIST discussion list at Linguist List and other lists the registration authority may consider relevant, inviting public review and input on the requested change.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Any list owner or individual is able to request notifications of change requests for particular regions or language families.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Comments that are received are published for other parties to review.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Based on consensus in comments received, a change request may be withdrawn or promoted to "candidate status".
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Three months prior to the end of an annual review cycle (typically in September), an announcement is sent to the LINGUIST discussion list and other lists regarding Candidate Status Change Requests.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] All requests remain open for review and comment through the end of the annual review cycle.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Decisions are announced at the end of the annual review cycle (typically in January).
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] At that time, requests may be adopted in whole or in part, amended and carried forward into the next review cycle, or rejected.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Rejections often include suggestions on how to modify proposals for resubmission.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] A public archive of every change request is maintained along with the decisions taken and the rationale for the decisions.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] Martin Haspelmath agrees with four of these points, but not the point about language change.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] He disagrees because any account of a language requires identifying it, and we can easily identify different stages of a language.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] He cites the original need for standardized language identifiers as having been "the economic significance of translation and software localization", for which purposes the ISO 639-1 and 639-2 standards were established.
[src:achuete/undetermined-language] But he raises doubts about industry need for the comprehensive coverage provided by ISO 639-3, including as it does "little-known languages of small communities that are never or hardly used in writing and that are often in danger of extinction".
